english:
  title: Preface to the Abbreviated History of the Three Kingdoms
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Our Eastern Land first established itself as a nation in the age of Tan'gun's ancient Chosŏn, a time of mist and memory when customs were simple and pure. When Ki-ja received his fief and taught the eight precepts, the beauty of culture and ritual propriety took root in our soil. Yet Wei Man's usurpation and the Han emperor's relentless campaigns brought only suffering—now four provinces, now two kingdoms, each conquest scattering our records like leaves. How lamentable that so much was lost.

    When Silla arose alongside Koguryŏ and Paekche in their tripartite balance, each kingdom kept its own histories, recording the events of their times. But what came down to us was distorted by rumor, clouded with strange tales, and muddied by provincial dialects and vulgar speech. The great Minister Kim Pu-sik of Koryŏ gathered these scattered accounts and shaped them into the History of the Three Kingdoms, following the model of Sima Qian's Records of the Grand Historian—with basic annals, biographical accounts, treatises, and tables, fifty volumes in all. Yet the same year was recorded twice, the same event duplicated, and crude language persisted like stubborn weeds. Readers found themselves lost, uncertain what was kept and what was cast aside.

    Now our sovereign lord, blessed with heaven-sent wisdom and devoted to the study of classics and history, has commanded his ministers—the Left Prime Minister Ha Ryun, the Chief Scholar of the Institute for Scholarly Worthies Yi Cham, and myself—to refine and consolidate these histories. Following the method of chronological arrangement, we have woven three kingdoms into one volume. Since Silla arose first and fell last, we have made its chronology our main thread, noting the reign dates of China alongside it to clarify the succession. Below we have marked the founding years of Koguryŏ and Paekche, then arranged all events by season and month. We place Silla first not by kingdom but as the central narrative; Koguryŏ and Paekche follow in order of their founding. Drawing from the annals and consulting the biographies, we have provided a skeleton to grasp the essential and joints to capture the detail. We have purged coarse speech and pruned away excess, removed the usurpers and elevated the virtuous, and appended our own modest reflections on what succeeded and what failed. Thus we have completed this work, titled the Abbreviated History of the Eastern Kingdom.

    Though the brush lacks force and the result seems unworthy of notice, the patterns of good governance and poor, the flourishing and decline of dynasties, offer lessons both to follow and to heed. Good and evil stand together in these pages. Should our lord, in moments of respite from ten thousand duties, deign to peruse this work, perhaps it might offer some small aid to the art of statecraft.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Tan'gun (檀君) was the legendary founder of ancient Chosŏn, considered the first Korean kingdom in traditional historiography.
  - key: ''
    value: Ki-ja (箕子) was a sage from China's Shang dynasty who, according to tradition, came to Korea and established a kingdom with eight precepts of governance.
  - key: ''
    value: Kim Pu-sik (金富軾, 1075–1151) was a Koryŏ statesman and historian who compiled the Samguk Sagi (History of the Three Kingdoms) in 1145.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Eastern Land' (海東) refers to Korea in classical Chinese geographical terminology.
  - key: ''
    value: Kwon Geun served under King Sejong as a high official and was instrumental in major scholarly projects of his reign.
